This very natural axiom is richer than it seems. For example, it implies a property of substitutability of equally strong arguments of the same polarity—a kind of property that is often called “anonymity” in social choice and decision theory. A kindred property to anonymity should also be required, for positive arguments to block negative arguments of the same strength. This blocking effect should not depend on the arguments themselves, but only on their position on the scale. Hence the axioms of positive and negative cancellation:
